chances are you already know a little bit about the roles and responsibilities of a personal trainer.</span><br /><br /><span style="color:rgb(42, 42, 42)">However, committing to a complete career change is kind of a big deal, so we thought we would quickly cover some of the roles and responsibilities that you can expect to have as a Level personal trainer in Glasgow.</span><br /><br /><span style="color:rgb(42, 42, 42)">Typically, personal trainers spend the majority of their time creating training programmes and carrying out 1-1 training sessions with clients.</span><br /><br /><span style="color:rgb(42, 42, 42)">Other roles and responsibilities include:</span><br /><br /><ul style="color:rgb(42, 42, 42)"><li>Carrying out gym inductions</li><li>Running group exercise classes</li><li>Working on the gym floor</li><li>Cleaning and maintaining equipment</li><li>Admin tasks</li></ul><br /><span style="color:rgb(42, 42, 42)">If you go on to complete a&nbsp;<a href="https://origympersonaltrainercourses.co.uk/course/nutrition-course"><span style="color:rgb(17, 85, 204); font-weight:400">Level 4 Nutrition for Sport qualification</span></a>, then you will be able to add creating client-specific meal plans to your list of roles and responsibilities.&nbsp;</span><br /><br /><span style="color:rgb(42, 42, 42)">One thing to know is that the roles and responsibilities of a Level 3 personal trainer can vary slightly depending on how you&rsquo;re employed.&nbsp;</span><br /><br /><span style="color:rgb(42, 42, 42)">For example, if you decide to work as a self-employed PT, you can expect to spend a lot more time on administrative tasks such as managing your accounts, sorting out tax, and marketing your business.</span><br /><br /><span style="color:rgb(42, 42, 42)">Meanwhile, personal trainers who are employed at a gym will spend more of their time carrying out gym inductions and working on the gym floor.</span></div>  <div class="paragraph"><strong><span>What Personal Training Qualifications Do I Need?</span></strong></div>  <div><div class="wsite-image wsite-image-border-none " style="padding-top:10px;padding-bottom:10px;margin-left:0;margin-right:0;text-align:center"> <a> <img src="https://www.strengthcoachglasgow.co.uk/uploads/1/2/3/3/123320581/image-2-qualified-pt_orig.png" alt="Picture" style="width:auto;max-width:100%" /> </a> <div style="display:block;font-size:90%"></div> </div></div>  <div class="paragraph"><span><span>If you want to know how to become a personal trainer in Glasgow, then the first thing you need to do is get the right qualifications.</span></span><br /><br /><span><span>You&rsquo;ll need to complete a Level 2 fitness instructor course and a Level 3 personal training course, often referred to as a personal training diploma.</span></span><br /><br /><span><span>Level 2 fitness instructor courses in Glasgow have no entry requirements, so as long as you are at least 16 years old you&rsquo;ll be able to enrol onto the course and get started with your exciting new career.&nbsp;</span></span><br /><br /><span><span>This course will cover the fundamentals of anatomy and physiology, the core principles of exercise, and teach you the basics of creating and delivering training programmes.</span></span><br /><br /><span><span>Once you&rsquo;ve completed your Level 2, you can then move onto a Level 3 personal trainer course.&nbsp;</span></span><br /><br /><span><span>This qualification goes into advanced detail of anatomy &amp; physiology, covers the principles of nutrition, and teaches you how to create training programmes that are specifically tailored to clients&rsquo; individual needs and exercise goals.</span></span><br /><span><span style="color:rgb(0, 0, 0); font-weight:400">How To Find The Best Personal Training Courses In Glasgow&nbsp;</span></span><span><span>When it comes to comparing personal trainer courses in Glasgow, there are a couple of things to think about.</span></span><br /><br /><span><span>Fortunately for you, we&rsquo;re about to break down what to look for in terms of accreditation and regulation, course quality, and how to choose the right study method!</span></span><br /><br /><strong><span><span style="color:rgb(67, 67, 67); font-weight:400"><em><font size="4">Course Accreditation &amp; Regulation Explained</font></em></span></span></strong><br /><br /><span><span>First things first, you will need to find a personal training certification that is regulated by an Ofqual approved awarding body, for example, Focus Awards, and accredited by REPs or CIMSPA.</span></span><br /><br /><span><span>Having a qualification that is regulated and accredited shows employers and clients that you are trained to a nationally agreed standard and therefore possess the right level of knowledge to carry out the role of a personal trainer.</span></span><br /><br /><span><span>Without an Ofqual regulated Level 3 personal trainer certification, you&rsquo;ll struggle to land a job in the industry as this is a requirement of the vast majority of employers.&nbsp;</span></span><br /><br /><span><span>If you thought that you could get around this by becoming a self-employed personal trainer in Glasgow, we&rsquo;re sorry to say that isn&rsquo;t an option! Without a regulated qualification, it's unlikely that an insurance provider will cover you.</span></span><br /><br /><span><span>Working as a PT without insurance is a huge risk that we would not recommend anybody to take, so unfortunately the cheap or even free personal training courses in Glasgow that are not regulated and accredited are not even worth the time spent completing them!</span></span><br /></div>  <div class="paragraph"><strong><span style="color:rgb(67, 67, 67)">Personal Training Courses Glasgow: Choosing Your Study Method</span></strong></div>  <div><div class="wsite-image wsite-image-border-none " style="padding-top:10px;padding-bottom:10px;margin-left:0;margin-right:0;text-align:center"> <a> <img src="https://www.strengthcoachglasgow.co.uk/uploads/1/2/3/3/123320581/image-3-study-method-graphic_orig.png" alt="Picture" style="width:auto;max-width:100%" /> </a> <div style="display:block;font-size:90%"></div> </div></div>  <div class="paragraph"><span style="color:rgb(42, 42, 42)">Outside of ensuring that you study a personal training course that is regulated and accredited, choosing your study method is probably the most important factor to consider when comparing Glasgow personal trainer courses.</span><br /><br /><span style="color:rgb(42, 42, 42)">Any reputable provider will offer 3 modes of study. Those are:</span><br /><br /><ul style="color:rgb(42, 42, 42)"><li>Full-time courses</li><li>Part-time courses&nbsp;</li><li>Online personal training courses&nbsp;</li></ul><br /><span style="color:rgb(42, 42, 42)">Out of all of these options, the &lsquo;best&rsquo; study method really depends on your individual preferences and circumstances.&nbsp;</span><br /><br /><span style="color:rgb(42, 42, 42)">For example, if you want to know how to become a personal trainer in Scotland but don&rsquo;t fancy making the journey to Glasgow,&nbsp;<a href="https://origympersonaltrainercourses.co.uk/course/online-personal-trainer-courses"><span style="color:rgb(17, 85, 204); font-weight:400">online personal trainer courses</span></a>&nbsp;are always a great option.</span><br /><br /><span style="color:rgb(42, 42, 42)">Online personal training courses with OriGym utilise an extensive range of top quality e-Learning resources that allow students to learn from a distance. Online students receive access to tons of remote learning resources and have email and telephone support with experienced fitness tutors.&nbsp;</span><br /><br /><span style="color:rgb(42, 42, 42)">This allows for a completely flexible way of studying personal trainer courses in Scotland, or wherever you like for that matter, as your physical attendance will only be required for your final practical assessments.&nbsp;</span><br /><br /><span style="color:rgb(42, 42, 42)">On the other hand, if you&rsquo;re based in or around Glasgow and think that you will learn better through face-to-face teaching, opting for a full-time course might be a better option for you.</span><br /><br /><span style="color:rgb(42, 42, 42)">Full-time courses are typically the fastest way to complete personal training courses in Glasgow as they involve 4 weeks of full-time teaching. For example, OriGym&rsquo;s full-time personal trainer courses in Glasgow involve a combination of practical learning in the gym and classroom-based lessons led by experienced fitness tutors.</span><br /><br /><span style="color:rgb(42, 42, 42)">If you can&rsquo;t commit to a full-time course but don&rsquo;t want to solely study online, part-time or &lsquo;blended learning&rsquo; courses are the perfect combination of both.</span><br /><br /><span style="color:rgb(42, 42, 42)">A part-time personal trainer course with a provider such as OriGym involves face-to-face learning during weekend workshops and online study utilising their award-nominated interactive learning platform.</span></div>  <div class="paragraph"><strong><span>Personal Trainer Courses Glasgow: Indicators of Quality</span></strong></div>  <div><div class="wsite-image wsite-image-border-none " style="padding-top:10px;padding-bottom:10px;margin-left:0;margin-right:0;text-align:center"> <a> <img src="https://www.strengthcoachglasgow.co.uk/uploads/1/2/3/3/123320581/image-4-indicators-of-quality_orig.png" alt="Picture" style="width:auto;max-width:100%" /> </a> <div style="display:block;font-size:90%"></div> </div></div>  <div class="paragraph"><span style="color:rgb(42, 42, 42)">Once you have decided on the right study method, the final step is to compare the quality of the various personal trainer certifications that you can study in Glasgow.</span><br /><br /><span style="color:rgb(42, 42, 42)">All Ofqual regulated courses will follow a very similar sort of &lsquo;curriculum&rsquo; that is outlined by the awarding body, for example, Focus Awards. This means that the course content for regulated and accredited courses is fairly similar.</span><br /><br /><span style="color:rgb(42, 42, 42)">So, how can you decide between regulated course providers? Here are 4 key indicators of course quality:</span><br /><br /><u style="color:rgb(42, 42, 42)">1. Standard of Teaching</u><br /><br /><span style="color:rgb(42, 42, 42)">When you&rsquo;re comparing personal training qualifications in Glasgow, it&rsquo;s important to consider the standard of teaching that a course provider offers.&nbsp;</span><br /><br /><span style="color:rgb(42, 42, 42)">It's a good idea to ask about the level of qualifications that tutors hold and their experience in the industry. These factors can really affect your overall experience of the course, so don&rsquo;t be afraid to ask direct questions about the tutor&rsquo;s qualifications, industry experience, and turnaround time for marking coursework.</span><br /><br /><span style="color:rgb(42, 42, 42)"><u>2. Tutor Availability&nbsp;</u></span><br /><br /><span style="color:rgb(42, 42, 42)">One thing that can really affect the quality of a course is tutor availability. If you&rsquo;ve already decided that a full-time course is the best option for you, then this isn&rsquo;t really an issue.&nbsp;</span><br /><br /><span style="color:rgb(42, 42, 42)">However, if you&rsquo;re thinking of opting for an online course, then you&rsquo;ll need to consider whether the tutor availability matches your study schedule. For example, if you&rsquo;re planning to study around a full-time job, then you will need to choose a course provider with tutors available on evenings and weekends.</span><br /><br /><span style="color:rgb(42, 42, 42)">OriGym is a great option for anybody looking for completely flexible study as they offer tutor support online and over the phone until 8pm on Mondays - Thursdays, until 7pm on Fridays, and tutors are available on wee